paragraphs.text: %md ## Regression Modeling to Predict Numerical Values using Neural Networks This notebook shows how to predict numerical values using multiple regression. Given demographic, purchase, and affinity card data for a set of customers, predict the number of years a customer remains at the same residence, as found in column YRS_RESIDENCE - a continuous variable. We will use the Neural Network algorithm. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database. Regression Modeling to Predict Numerical Values using Neural Networks

This notebook shows how to predict numerical values using multiple regression. paragraphs.text:
%r

library(ORE)
library(lattice)

options(ore.warn.order=FALSE)

paragraphs.title: Prepare the dataset combining customer data with supplemental demographics
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.sync(query = c("QUERY_CUSTOMERS" = 'SELECT CUST_ID, CUST_GENDER, CUST_MARITAL_STATUS, CUST_YEAR_OF_BIRTH AGE, CUST_INCOME_LEVEL, CUST_CREDIT_LIMIT FROM SH.CUSTOMERS'))
ore.sync(query = c("QUERY_DEMO_DF" =  'SELECT CUST_ID, EDUCATION, AFFINITY_CARD, HOUSEHOLD_SIZE, OCCUPATION, YRS_RESIDENCE, Y_BOX_GAMES FROM SH.SUPPLEMENTARY_DEMOGRAPHICS'))
CUST_DF <- merge(QUERY_CUSTOMERS,QUERY_DEMO_DF)

paragraphs.title: Split data into randomly selected 60% sample for train and 40% test
paragraphs.text:
%r

set.seed(123)
rownames(CUST_DF) <- CUST_DF$CUST_ID

sampleSize <- .6 * nrow(CUST_DF)
index <- sample(1:nrow(CUST_DF),sampleSize)

# Create training data set
CUST_DF.train <- CUST_DF[index,]

# Create test data set
CUST_DF.test <- CUST_DF[setdiff(1:nrow(CUST_DF),index),]

class(CUST_DF.train)
cat("\nTraining data: ")
dim(CUST_DF.train)

class(CUST_DF.test)
cat("\nTest data: ")
dim(CUST_DF.test)

paragraphs.title: Build a SVM Linear regression model for predicting YRS_RESIDENCE using default model settings and assigning model name
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.exec("BEGIN DBMS_DATA_MINING.DROP_MODEL(model_name=> 'NN_REGRESSION_MODEL'); EXCEPTION WHEN others THEN null;END;")

svm.mod1 <- ore.odmNN(YRS_RESIDENCE~.-CUST_ID, CUST_DF.train, "regression", odm.settings=list(model_name="NN_REGRESSION_MODEL"))

paragraphs.text: %md ### Examples of possible setting overrides for NN If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link: -- Algorithm Settings: Neural Network -- Shared Settings: All algorithms -- Specify a row weight column 'ODMS_ROW_WEIGHT_COLUMN_NAME' : '' -- Specify a missing value treatment method for the training data. This setting does not affect the scoring data. The default value is `ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_AUTO`. The option `ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_MEAN_MODE` replaces missing values with the mean (numeric attributes) or the mode (categorical attributes) both at build time and apply time where appropriate. The option `ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_AUTO` performs different strategies for different algorithms. When `ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT` is set to `ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_DELETE_ROW`, the rows in the training data that contain missing values are deleted. However, if you want to replicate this missing value treatment in the scoring data, then you must perform the transformation explicitly. 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT' : 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_AUTO' -- Specify the Neural Network architecture. The default number of layers is 1, and the default activation function is NNET_ACTIVATIONS_LOG_SIG (Log Sigmoid). The default number of nodes per layer is the number of attributes or 50 (if the number of attributes > 50). Be careful with quotes around NNET_ACTIVATIONS. 'NNET_HIDDEN_LAYERS' = '3' 'NNET_NODES_PER_LAYER' = '8,8,2' 'NNET_ACTIVATIONS' = "'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_TANH', 'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_LOG_SIG', 'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_ARCTAN'" -- Specify the Heldaside options for Regularization. If the total number of training rows is greater than 50000, the default is NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE, otherwise it is NNET_REGULARIZER_NONE. The held ratio for the held-aside method is 0.25 by default. With NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE, the training process is stopped early if the network performance on the validation data fails to improve for NNET_HELDASIDE_MAX_FAIL epochs in a row (default is 6). 'NNET_REGULARIZER' = 'NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE' 'NNET_HELDASIDE_RATIO' = '0.25' 'NNET_HELDASIDE_MAX_FAIL' = '6' -- Specify the L2 regularization parameter, with a default of 1. Cannot be used with NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE. 'NNET_REG_LAMBDA' = '1' -- Specify the number of iterations, which is 200 by default for LBFGS solver and 10000 for the ADAM solver. The default convergence tolerance setting is 0.000001. 'NNET_ITERATIONS' = '200' 'NNET_TOLERANCE' = '0.000001' 'ODMS_RANDOM_SEED' = '0' -- Specify details on the LBFGS Solver. The number of historical copies kept in L-BFGS solver is defined by LBFGS_HISTORY_DEPTH. When the number of iterations is smaller than the history depth, the Hessian computed by L-BFGS is accurate, otherwise the Hessian computed by L-BFGS is an approximation. Typically, the value is between 3 and 10. 'LBFGS_HISTORY_DEPTH' = '10' -- Specify the gradient infinity norm tolerance for L-BFGS. The default value is 1E-9. 'LBFGS_GRADIENT_TOLERANCE' = '0.0000001' -- Specify how to set the initial approximation of the inverse Hessian at the beginning of each iteration. If the value is set to be LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_ENABLE, then we approximate the initial inverse Hessian with Oren-Luenberger scaling. If it is set to be LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_DISABLE, then we use identity as the approximation of the inverse Hessian at the beginning of each iteration 'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN' = 'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_ENABLE' 'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN' = 'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_DISABLE'

msg.data:
Examples of possible setting overrides for NN

If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm

A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link:

– Algorithm Settings: Neural Network

– Shared Settings: All algorithms

– Specify a row weight column

'ODMS_ROW_WEIGHT_COLUMN_NAME' : '<row_weight_column_name>'

– Specify a missing value treatment method for the training data. This setting does not affect the scoring data. The default value is ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_AUTO. The option ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_MEAN_MODE replaces missing values with the mean (numeric attributes) or the mode (categorical attributes) both at build time and apply time where appropriate. The option ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_AUTO performs different strategies for different algorithms. When ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT is set to ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_DELETE_ROW, the rows in the training data that contain missing values are deleted. However, if you want to replicate this missing value treatment in the scoring data, then you must perform the transformation explicitly.

'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT' : 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_AUTO'

– Specify the Neural Network architecture. The default number of layers is 1, and the default activation function is NNET_ACTIVATIONS_LOG_SIG (Log Sigmoid). The default number of nodes per layer is the number of attributes or 50 (if the number of attributes > 50). Be careful with quotes around NNET_ACTIVATIONS.

'NNET_HIDDEN_LAYERS' = '3'
'NNET_NODES_PER_LAYER' = '8,8,2'
'NNET_ACTIVATIONS' = "'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_TANH', 'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_LOG_SIG', 'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_ARCTAN'"

– Specify the Heldaside options for Regularization. If the total number of training rows is greater than 50000, the default is NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE, otherwise it is NNET_REGULARIZER_NONE. The held ratio for the held-aside method is 0.25 by default. With NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE, the training process is stopped early if the network performance on the validation data fails to improve for NNET_HELDASIDE_MAX_FAIL epochs in a row (default is 6).

'NNET_REGULARIZER' = 'NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE'
'NNET_HELDASIDE_RATIO' = '0.25'
'NNET_HELDASIDE_MAX_FAIL' = '6'

– Specify the L2 regularization parameter, with a default of 1. Cannot be used with NNET_REGULARIZER_HELDASIDE.

'NNET_REG_LAMBDA' = '1'

– Specify the number of iterations, which is 200 by default for LBFGS solver and 10000 for the ADAM solver. The default convergence tolerance setting is 0.000001.

'NNET_ITERATIONS' = '200'
'NNET_TOLERANCE' = '0.000001'
'ODMS_RANDOM_SEED' = '0'

– Specify details on the LBFGS Solver. The number of historical copies kept in L-BFGS solver is defined by LBFGS_HISTORY_DEPTH. When the number of iterations is smaller than the history depth, the Hessian computed by L-BFGS is accurate, otherwise the Hessian computed by L-BFGS is an approximation. Typically, the value is between 3 and 10.

'LBFGS_HISTORY_DEPTH' = '10'

– Specify the gradient infinity norm tolerance for L-BFGS. The default value is 1E-9.

'LBFGS_GRADIENT_TOLERANCE' = '0.0000001'

– Specify how to set the initial approximation of the inverse Hessian at the beginning of each iteration. If the value is set to be LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_ENABLE, then we approximate the initial inverse Hessian with Oren-Luenberger scaling. If it is set to be LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_DISABLE, then we use identity as the approximation of the inverse Hessian at the beginning of each iteration

'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN' = 'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_ENABLE'
'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN' = 'LBFGS_SCALE_HESSIAN_DISABLE'

paragraphs.title: Using a Single Layer with 4 Neurons with specific Activation
paragraphs.text:
%r

settings <- list(NNET_HIDDEN_LAYERS = 1,
                 NNET_NODES_PER_LAYER = '4',
                 NNET_ACTIVATIONS = "'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_TANH'")
                 
svm.mod2 <- ore.odmNN(YRS_RESIDENCE~.-CUST_ID, CUST_DF.train, "regression", odm.settings = settings)

paragraphs.title: Using a 3 Layers with 8,8,2 Neurons with specific Activations
paragraphs.text:
%r

settings <- list(NNET_HIDDEN_LAYERS = 3,
                 NNET_NODES_PER_LAYER = c('8','8','4'),
                 NNET_ACTIVATIONS = c("'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_TANH'","'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_LOG_SIG'", "'NNET_ACTIVATIONS_LINEAR'")
                 )  
svm.mod3 <- ore.odmNN(YRS_RESIDENCE~.-CUST_ID, CUST_DF.train, 'regression', odm.settings = settings)

paragraphs.title: Make predictions using test data and display results
paragraphs.text:
%r

RES_DF <- predict(svm.mod3, CUST_DF.test, supplemental.cols='YRS_RESIDENCE')

paragraphs.title: Model quality statistics on the TEST dataset
paragraphs.text:
%r

CoefficientOfDeterminationR2 <- summary(svm.mod3)$r.squared
MeanAbsoluteError <- (sum(abs(RES_DF['YRS_RESIDENCE'] - RES_DF['PREDICTION'])))/nrow(RES_DF['YRS_RESIDENCE'])
MeanSquaredError <- (sum((RES_DF['YRS_RESIDENCE'] - RES_DF['PREDICTION'])^2))/nrow(RES_DF['YRS_RESIDENCE'])
RootMeanSquaredError <- sqrt(MeanSquaredError)

cat('R^2: ', CoefficientOfDeterminationR2)
cat('MAE: ', MeanAbsoluteError)
cat('MSE: ', MeanSquaredError)
cat('RMSE: ', RootMeanSquaredError)

paragraphs.title: Plot the predicted and actual years of residence
paragraphs.text:
%r

x <- ore.pull(RES_DF[['PREDICTION']])
y <- ore.pull(RES_DF[['YRS_RESIDENCE']])
n <- length(x)

dotplot(y~x, xlab = "PREDICTION", ylab = "YRS_RESIDENCE", 
        panel = function(x,y) {
          panel.dotplot(x,y)
          panel.abline(0, 1, col="red")
        }, 
        xlim=c(0,14.5), 
        ylim=c(0,14.5),
        scales=list(y=list(tick.number=8), x=list(tick.number=8)), 
        main="The prediction vs. actual value for years of residence")

paragraphs.title: Plot the residuals
paragraphs.text:
%r

xyplot(y-x~x, xlab = "PREDICTION", ylab = "RESIDUAL", 
       panel = function(x,y) {
         panel.xyplot(x,y)
         panel.abline(0, 0, col="red")
       }, 
       xlim=c(0,8.5), 
       ylim=c(-7,8.5),
       scales=list(y=list(tick.number=8), x=list(tick.number=8)), 
       main="Prediction of Years of Residence vs. Residuals")

paragraphs.title: Materialize NN_TEST_DATA for use in query below

paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT CUST_ID,
 round(PREDICTION_YRS_RES,3) PRED_YRS_RES,
 RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
 RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
 RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE
 FROM (SELECT CUST_ID,
              PREDICTION(NN_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *) PREDICTION_YRS_RES,
              PREDICTION_DETAILS(NN_REGRESSION_MODEL USING *) PD
       FROM NN_TEST_DATA
       WHERE CUST_ID < 100015
       ORDER BY CUST_ID) OUT,
       XMLTABLE('/Details'
                PASSING OUT.PD
                COLUMNS 
                "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]') 
                OUTPRED
